** Pinocchio: An Alternative Origin Story Exploring the Grandest Questions=
 of Existence (https://www.brainpickings.org/2016/09/12/pinocchio-alessand=
ro-sanna/?mc_cid=3D1ffb15db80&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID])
------------------------------------------------------------

http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/1592701914/braipick-20?mc_cid=3D1ff=
b15db80&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]

=E2=80=9CMyths are made for the imagination to breathe life into them=2C=
=E2=80=9D Albert Camus wrote (http://literaryjukebox.brainpickings.org/pos=
t/150225900697?mc_cid=3D1ffb15db80&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) . Ada Lovelace=2C t=
he world=E2=80=99s first computer programmer (https://www.brainpickings.or=
g/2014/12/10/ada-lovelace-walter-isaacson-innovators/?mc_cid=3D1ffb15db80&=
mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) =2C observed a century earlier as she contemplated the=
 nature of the imagination and its three core faculties (https://www.brain=
pickings.org/2015/12/10/ada-lovelace-imagination/?mc_cid=3D1ffb15db80&mc_e=
id=3D[UNIQID]) : =E2=80=9CImagination is the Discovering Faculty=2C pre-e=
minently=E2=80=A6 that which penetrates into the unseen worlds around us.=
=E2=80=9D

This =E2=80=9Cdiscovering faculty=E2=80=9D of the imagination=2C which bre=
athes life into both the most captivating myths and the deepest layers of=
 reality=2C is what animated Italian artist Alessandro Sanna one winter af=
ternoon when he glimpsed a most unusual tree branch from the window of a m=
oving train =E2=80=94 a branch that looked like a sensitive human silhouet=
te=2C mid-fall or mid-embrace.

As Sanna cradled the enchanting image in his mind and began sketching it=
=2C he realized that something about the =E2=80=9Cbody language=E2=80=9D o=
f the branch reminded him of a small=2C delicate=2C terminally ill child h=
e=E2=80=99d gotten to know during his visits to Turin=E2=80=99s Pediatric=
 Hospital. In beholding this common ground of tender fragility=2C Sanna=E2=
=80=99s imagination leapt to a foundational myth of his nation=E2=80=99s s=
torytelling =E2=80=94 the Pinocchio story.

In the astonishingly beautiful and tenderhearted Pinocchio: The Origin Sto=
ry (http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/1592701914/braipick-20?mc_cid=
=3D1ffb15db80&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) (public library (http://www.worldcat.org=
/title/pinocchio-the-origin-story/oclc/956671527&referer=3Dbrief_results?m=
c_cid=3D1ffb15db80&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) )=2C Sanna imagines an alternative=
 prequel to the beloved story=2C a wordless genesis myth of the wood that=
 became Pinocchio=2C radiating a larger cosmogony of life=2C death=2C and=
 the transcendent continuity between the two.

http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/1592701914/braipick-20?mc_cid=3D1ff=
b15db80&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]

A fitting follow-up to The River (https://www.brainpickings.org/2014/02/27=
/the-river-alessandro-sanna/?mc_cid=3D1ffb15db80&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) =E2=
=80=94 Sanna=E2=80=99s exquisite visual memoir of life on the Po River in=
 Northern Italy=2C reflecting on the seasonality of human existence =E2=80=
=94 this imaginative masterwork dances with the cosmic unknowns that eclip=
se human life and the human mind with their enormity: questions like what=
 life is=2C how it began=2C and what happens when it ends.

Origin myths have been our oldest sensemaking mechanism for wresting meani=
ng out of these as-yet-unanswered=2C perhaps unanswerable (https://www.bra=
inpickings.org/2014/09/16/hannah-arendt-the-life-of-the-mind/?mc_cid=3D1ff=
b15db80&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) questions. But rather than an argument with sc=
ience and our secular sensibility=2C Sanna=E2=80=99s lyrical celebration o=
f myth embodies Margaret Mead=E2=80=99s insistence on the importance of po=
etic truth in the age of facts (https://www.brainpickings.org/2014/12/16/m=
argaret-mead-santa-claus-myth-deception/?mc_cid=3D1ffb15db80&mc_eid=3D[UN=
IQID]) .

http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/1592701914/braipick-20?mc_cid=3D1ff=
b15db80&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]

The tree is an organic choice for this unusual cosmogony =E2=80=94 after a=
ll=2C trees have inspired centuries of folk tales around the world (https:=
//www.brainpickings.org/2016/06/09/strange-trees/?mc_cid=3D1ffb15db80&mc_e=
id=3D[UNIQID]) ; a 17th-century English gardener marveled at how they =E2=
