** The Private Person and the Public Persona: Borges on the Divided Self (=
https://www.brainpickings.org/2016/09/06/borges-and-i/?mc_cid=3D1ffb15db80=
&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID])
------------------------------------------------------------

http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/0811216993/braipick-20?mc_cid=3D1ff=
b15db80&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]

=E2=80=9CA person=E2=80=99s identity=2C=E2=80=9D Amin Maalouf wrote as he=
 contemplated what he so poetically called the genes of the soul (https://=
www.brainpickings.org/2015/08/20/amin-maalouf-identity/?mc_cid=3D1ffb15db8=
0&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) =2C =E2=80=9Cis like a pattern drawn on a tightly st=
retched parchment. Touch just one part of it=2C just one allegiance=2C and=
 the whole person will react=2C the whole drum will sound.=E2=80=9D And ye=
t=2C inseparable as the parts may be from the whole=2C we each contain mul=
titudes =E2=80=94 not only psychologically=2C but even biologically (https=
://www.brainpickings.org/2016/08/10/i-contain-multitudes-ed-yong/?mc_cid=
=3D1ffb15db80&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) =E2=80=94 nowhere more so than when it c=
omes to the bifurcation between our inner and outer selves. =E2=80=9CNothi=
ng and nobody exists in this world whose very being does not presuppose a=
 spectator=2C=E2=80=9D Hannah Arendt observed in her insightful inquiry in=
to being vs. appearing and our impulse for self-display (https://www.brain=
pickings.org/2015/10/14/hannah-arendt-life-of-the-mind-being-appearing/?mc=
_cid=3D1ffb15db80&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) . For each of us=2C there is a publi=
c persona encasing
the private person=2C an aspirational self radiating from the real self.

However integrated the our layered identity (https://www.brainpickings.org=
/2016/03/02/amelie-rorty-the-identities-of-persons/?mc_cid=3D1ffb15db80&mc=
_eid=3D[UNIQID]) may be=2C our twined nature stands like a stereogram =E2=
=80=94 two separate and noticeably different views=2C composed into a sing=
le three-dimensional image of personhood only through the special focal me=
chanism of our own consciousness.

No one has addressed this existential sundering more elegantly than Jorge=
 Luis Borges (August 24=2C 1899=E2=80=93June 14=2C 1986) in =E2=80=9CBorge=
s and I=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94 his classic parable of selfhood=2C exploring th=
e divide between private person and public persona that each of us must li=
ve with and live into. It appears in Labyrinths (http://www.amazon.com/exe=
c/obidos/ASIN/0811216993/braipick-20?mc_cid=3D1ffb15db80&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID=
]) (public library (http://www.worldcat.org/title/labyrinths-selected-stor=
ies-other-writings/oclc/260942&referer=3Dbrief_results?mc_cid=3D1ffb15db80=
&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) ) =E2=80=94 a collection of Borges=E2=80=99s stories=
=2C essays=2C parables=2C and other writings=2C originally published in 19=
62.

http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/0811216993/braipick-20?mc_cid=3D1ff=
b15db80&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]

Borges writes:

The other one=2C the one called Borges=2C is the one things happen to. I w=
alk through the streets of Buenos Aires and stop for a moment=2C perhaps m=
echanically now=2C to look at the arch of an entrance hall and the grillwo=
rk on the gate; I know of Borges from the mail and see his name on a list=
 of professors or in a biographical dictionary. I like hourglasses=2C maps=
=2C eighteenth-century typography=2C the taste of coffee and the prose of=
 Stevenson; he shares these preferences=2C but in a vain way that turns th=
em into the attributes of an actor. It would be an exaggeration to say tha=
t ours is a hostile relationship; I live=2C let myself go on living=2C so=
 that Borges may contrive his literature=2C and this literature justifies=
 me. It is no effort for me to confess that he has achieved some valid pag=
es=2C but those pages cannot save me=2C perhaps because what is good belon=
gs to no one=2C not even to him=2C but rather to the language and to tradi=
tion. Besides=2C I am destined to perish=2C definitively=2C and
only some instant of myself can survive in him. Little by little=2C I am g=
iving over everything to him=2C though I am quite aware of his perverse cu=
stom of falsifying and magnifying things. Spinoza knew that all things lon=
g to persist in their being; the stone eternally wants to be a stone and t=
he tiger a tiger. I shall remain in Borges=2C not in myself (if it is true=
 that I am someone)=2C but I recognize myself less in his books than in ma=
ny others or in the laborious strumming of a guitar. Years ago I tried to=
 free myself from him and went from the mythologies of the suburbs to the=
 games with time and infinity=2C but those games belong to Borges now and=
 I shall have to imagine other things. Thus my life is a flight and I lose=
 everything and everything belongs to oblivion=2C or to him.

I do not know which of us has written this page.

=E2=80=9CBorges and I=E2=80=9D went on to inspire some of the greatest wri=
ters of the past century to reflect on the divided self in hand-drawn self=
-portraits (https://www.brainpickings.org/2013/11/08/whos-writing-this-not=
ations-on-the-authorial-i-with-self-portraits/?mc_cid=3D1ffb15db80&mc_eid=
=3D[UNIQID]) . Complement it with philosopher Amelie Rorty on the seven l=
ayers of personhood in literature and life (https://www.brainpickings.org/=
2016/03/02/amelie-rorty-the-identities-of-persons/?mc_cid=3D1ffb15db80&mc_=
eid=3D[UNIQID]) and Rebecca Goldstein on what makes you and your childhoo=
d self the same person (https://www.brainpickings.org/2014/10/07/rebecca-g=
oldstein-personal-identity/?mc_cid=3D1ffb15db80&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) despit=
e a lifetime of change=2C then revisit Borges on writing (https://www.brai=
npickings.org/2013/09/03/jorge-luis-borges-on-writing/?mc_cid=3D1ffb15db80=
&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) =2C public opinion (https://www.brainpickings.org/201=
5/08/24/borges-success/?mc_cid=3D1ffb15db80&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) =2C and ou=
r private participation in collective joy and collective tragedy (https://=
www.brainpickings.org/2016/08/24/borges-jfk-collective-tragedy-collective-=
