er-wallace/?mc_cid=3D1ffb15db80&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) =2C Italo Calvino (htt=
ps://www.brainpickings.org/2013/06/10/italo-calvino-on-writing/?mc_cid=3D1=
ffb15db80&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) =2C and William Faulkner (https://www.brainp=
ickings.org/2014/09/25/william-faulkner-university-of-virginia-recording/?=
mc_cid=3D1ffb15db80&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) =E2=80=94 Egan considers the act o=
f writing as a form of vital self-care:

When I=E2=80=99m not writing I feel an awareness that something=E2=80=99s=
 missing. If I go a long time=2C it becomes worse. I become depressed. The=
re=E2=80=99s something vital that=E2=80=99s not happening. A certain slow=
 damage starts to occur. I can coast along awhile without it=2C but then m=
y limbs go numb. Something bad is happening to me=2C and I know it. The lo=
nger I wait=2C the harder it is to start again.

When I=E2=80=99m writing=2C especially if it=E2=80=99s going well=2C I=E2=
=80=99m living in two different dimensions: this life I=E2=80=99m living n=
ow=2C which I enjoy very much=2C and this completely other world I=E2=80=
=99m inhabiting that no one else knows about.

For Egan=2C as for many artists=2C this different mode of inhabiting reali=
ty embodies pioneering psychologist Mihalyi Csikszentmihalyi=E2=80=99s con=
