She ends by offering three points of advice to aspiring writers:

* Read at the level at which you want to write. Reading is the nourishment=
 that feeds the kind of writing you want to do. If what you really love to=
 read is y=2C it might be hard for you to write x.
* Exercising is a good analogy for writing. If you=E2=80=99re not used to=
 exercising you want to avoid it forever. If you=E2=80=99re used to it=2C=
 it feels uncomfortable and strange not to. No matter where you are in you=
r writing career=2C the same is true for writing. Even fifteen minutes a d=
ay will keep you in the habit.
* You can only write regularly if you=E2=80=99re willing to write badly. Y=
ou can=E2=80=99t write regularly and well. One should accept bad writing a=
s a way of priming the pump=2C a warm-up exercise that allows you to write=
 well.

Complement Why We Write (http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/0452298156=
/braipick-20?mc_cid=3D1ffb15db80&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) with great writers=E2=
