** The M=C3=B6bius Strip of Remembering and Forgetting: Teju Cole on How t=
he Paradox of Photography Captures the Central Anxiety of Existence (https=
://www.brainpickings.org/2016/09/12/teju-cole-known-and-strange-things-pho=
tography/?mc_cid=3D1ffb15db80&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID])
------------------------------------------------------------

http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/0812989783/braipick-20?mc_cid=3D1ff=
b15db80&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]

=E2=80=9CThe life that you live in order to photograph it is already=2C at=
 the outset=2C a commemoration of itself=2C=E2=80=9D Italo Calvino wrote i=
n 1970 as he reflected on photography and the art of presence (https://www=
=2Ebrainpickings.org/2015/10/15/italo-calvino-difficult-loves-photography/?m=
c_cid=3D1ffb15db80&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) . That same decade=2C Susan Sontag=
 considered how photography mediates life=E2=80=99s relationship with deat=
h (https://www.brainpickings.org/2016/07/22/susan-sontag-peter-hujar-portr=
aits-in-life-and-death/?mc_cid=3D1ffb15db80&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) =2C that u=
ltimate commemoration=2C observing: =E2=80=9CWe no longer study the art of=
 dying=2C a regular discipline and hygiene in older cultures; but all eyes=
=2C at rest=2C contain that knowledge. The body knows. And the camera show=
s=2C inexorably.=E2=80=9D A year later=2C she would go on to expand on the=
se ideas in her timeless treatise on photography=2C exploring its function=
 not only as commemoration but as =E2=80=9Caesthetic consumerism=E2=80=9D=
 (https://www.brainpickings.org/2013/09/16/susan-sontag-on-photography-soc=
ial-media/?mc_cid=3D1ffb15db80&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) =E2=80=94 an insight wh=
ich time has
proven astoundingly prescient as we confront the insatiable voraciousness=
 of visual culture in the age of the social web.

Nearly half a century later=2C the Nigerian-American writer=2C art histori=
an=2C and photographer Teju Cole =E2=80=94 perhaps Sontag=E2=80=99s closes=
t contemporary counterpart =E2=80=94 examines this dual role of photograph=
y as commemoration and consumerism in an essay titled =E2=80=9CMemories of=
 Things Unseen=2C=E2=80=9D found in the altogether spectacular Known and S=
trange Things: Essays (http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/0812989783/b=
raipick-20?mc_cid=3D1ffb15db80&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) (public library (http:/=
/www.worldcat.org/title/known-and-strange-things-essays/oclc/929917329&ref=
erer=3Dbrief_results?mc_cid=3D1ffb15db80&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) ).

Teju Cole (Photography: Martin Lengemann)

Cole writes:

Photography is inescapably a memorial art. It selects=2C out of the flow o=
f time=2C a moment to be preserved=2C with the moments before and after fa=
lling away like sheer cliffs. At a dinner party earlier this year=2C I was=
 in conversation with someone who asked me to define photography. I sugges=
ted that it is about retention: not only the ability to make an image dire=
ctly out of the interaction between light and the tangible world but also=
 the possibility of saving that image. A shadow thrown onto a wall is not=
 photography. But if the wall is photosensitive and the shadow remains aft=
er the body has moved on=2C that is photography. Human creativity=2C since=
 the beginning of art=2C has found ways to double the visible world. What=
 photography did was to give the world a way to double its own appearance:=
 the photograph results directly from what is=2C from the light that trave=
ls from a body through an aperture onto a surface.

But when the photograph outlives the body 00 when people die=2C scenes cha=
nge=2C trees grow or are chopped down =E2=80=94 it becomes a memorial. And=
 when the thing photographed is a work of art or architecture that has bee=
n destroyed=2C this effect is amplified even further. A painting=2C sculpt=
ure=2C or temple=2C as a record of both human skill and emotion=2C is alre=
ady a site of memory; when its only remaining trace is a photograph=2C tha=
t photograph becomes a memorial to a memory. Such a photograph is shadowed=
 by its vanished ancestor.

But memory itself is an imperfect memorial: The events of our lives are si=
milarly shadowed by the photographs of those events. Who hasn=E2=80=99t lo=
oked at an early childhood photograph of oneself=2C predating the age of c=
onscious remembering=2C and not felt the mirage of a memory in beholding t=
hat moment? In those instances=2C what we remember is what was captured=2C=
 which releases in us a believable conjecture about what was=2C and the co=
njecture becomes calcified into an unremembered memory.

The same M=C3=B6bius strip of representation and remembrance=2C Cole sugge=
sts=2C exists in our collective memory. He recounts a visit to the Metropo=
litan Museum=E2=80=99s collection of works from the ancient Middle East=2C=
 just as the news media were reporting on the accelerating destruction of=
 artifacts in Syria and Iraq. (That the =E2=80=9Cnews=E2=80=9D as we know=
 it is an overwhelmingly photography-driven industry=2C selling the immedi=
acy of the present using what is invariably in the past as its chief curre=
ncy=2C is a paradox so self-evident that it need not be belabored.) Cole w=
rites:

Next to a selection of second- and third-century Syrian gravestones (many=
 of them fresh with the pain of loss and inscribed with the names of the d=
ead and the word =E2=80=9CAlas!=E2=80=9D)=2C there was an old photograph r=
eproduced from a book of the Temple of Bel=2C an important archaeological=
 complex in Palmyra. About a week later=2C the iconoclastic fanatics of IS=
IS blew up this very temple. The photograph was unchanged; it was still th=
ere on the wall of Room 406 at the Met=2C but it was now filled up with th=
e loss of what it depicted. The Roman-era columns of the temple still stan=
d in rows in the grainy image =E2=80=94 ravaged by time=2C but standing. I=
n life=2C they=E2=80=99re gone.

The Institute for Digital Archaeology=2C a joint project of Harvard and Ox=
ford Universities=2C uses sophisticated imaging techniques to aid conserva=
tion=2C epigraphy=2C archaeology=2C and art history. One of the institute=
=E2=80=99s current efforts=2C the Million Image Database project=2C involv=
es photographing artifacts that are at risk of being destroyed for militar=
y or religious reasons=2C a bleak necessity in a world in which the beauty=
 or importance of an object does not guarantee its safety. The goal of the=
 project is to distribute up to five thousand modified cameras=2C to profe=
ssionals and to amateurs=2C and use them to capture a million 3-D images.=
 Already=2C more than a thousand cameras have been distributed=2C and the=
 3-D data from them are being received (though the directors of the projec=
t=2C to protect their associates on the ground=2C are leaving a lag of sev=
eral months before they make the images publicly available). In the event=
 of some of the objects being destroyed=2C the detailed visual
record could be enough to facilitate a reconstruction. Photography is used=
 to ward off total oblivion.

The camera obscura=2C one of the 100 ideas that changed photography (https=
://www.brainpickings.org/2012/10/24/100-ideas-that-changed-photography/?mc=
_cid=3D1ffb15db80&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID])

And yet photography=2C after all=2C is a technology =E2=80=94 both of thin=
g and of thought =E2=80=94 and like any technology=2C it is animated by a=
 dual capacity for good and evil. Parallel to this constructive use of pho=
tography as reconstruction of collective memory=2C Cole points to its dest=
ructive counterpart =E2=80=94 its use in monitoring and manipulation=2C a=
 kind of =E2=80=9Caesthetic control=E2=80=9D to Sontag=E2=80=99s =E2=80=9C=
aesthetic consumerism.=E2=80=9D He writes:

Our own appearances and faces are now stored and saved in hundreds=2C thou=
sands=2C of photographs: photographs made by ourselves=2C photographs made=
 by others. Our faces are becoming not only unforgettable but inescapable.=
 There is so much documentation of each life=2C each scene and event=2C th=
at the effect of this incessant visual notation becomes difficult to disti=
nguish from surveillance. And in fact=2C much of the intent behind the col=
lection of these images is indeed surveillance: the government retains our=
 images in order to fight terrorism=2C and corporations harvest everything=
 they can about us in order to sell us things.

But the most disquieting aspect of this perpetual photographic documentati=
on is that we have reached a point where these images of us will long outl=
ive us and might=2C in theory=2C last forever. =E2=80=9CAll eternity is in=
 the moment=2C=E2=80=9D (https://www.brainpickings.org/2014/09/10/mary-oli=
ver-on-punctuation/?mc_cid=3D1ffb15db80&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) but when the m=
oment ceases to be ephemeral and instead lasts forever=2C it ceases to exi=
st. Paradoxically=2C rather than furnishing a greater gateway to eternity=
=2C eradicating the moment extinguishes eternity altogether. When everythi=
ng is eternal=2C nothing is eternal.

Sequenced image of a rotating sulky wheel with self-portrait by Eadweard M=
uybridge=2C who changed modern consciousness by freezing the flow of exist=
ence (https://www.brainpickings.org/2016/05/26/river-of-shadows-rebecca-so=
lnit-muybridge/?mc_cid=3D1ffb15db80&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) .

Cole illustrates our confused relationship to temporality with a sobering=
 anecdote of a self-annihilating exchange with a friend via SnapChat=2C on=
e of our few deliberately ephemeral technologies:

The voiding of the record on Snapchat was startling. But it was also a rel=
ief. Our real selves remained=2C but the photographs were no longer there=
=2C and something about this felt like a sequence more preferable to the o=
ther way around=2C where the image lives on and the model is irretrievable=
=2E But just as nothing can be permanently retained=2C nothing is ever reall=
y gone. Somewhere out there=2C perhaps in the Cloud or in some clandestine=
 server=2C is the optical afterimage of our interaction: the faces=2C the=
 shoes=2C the texts. In these all-seeing days=2C the traffic between memor=
y and forgetting becomes untrackable. Photography is at the nerve center o=
f our paradoxical memorial impulses: we need it there for how it helps us=
 frame our losses=2C but we can also sense it crowding in on ongoing exper=
ience=2C imposing closure on what should still be open.

I=E2=80=99m reminded of Sarah Manguso=E2=80=99s magnificent meditation on=
 time and memory (https://www.brainpickings.org/2015/03/31/ongoingness-sar=
ah-manguso/?mc_cid=3D1ffb15db80&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) =2C in which she cryst=
allized the paradox: =E2=80=9CPerhaps all anxiety might derive from a fixa=
tion on moments =E2=80=94 an inability to accept life as ongoing.=E2=80=9D=
 I take from Cole =E2=80=94 an inference that no doubt suffers the typical=
 bedevilments of interpretation (https://www.brainpickings.org/2015/01/16/=
susan-sontag-against-interpretation-content/?mc_cid=3D1ffb15db80&mc_eid=3D=
[UNIQID]) =E2=80=94 that the camera lens has become the supreme focal poi=
nt of that existential anxiety=2C through which we exorcise the ultimate f=
ixation on freezing the flow of existence. To commemorate life in the act=
 of living it seems to be the human condition =E2=80=94 or the human curse=
=2E

Complement the wholly terrific Known and Strange Things (http://www.amazon=
=2Ecom/exec/obidos/ASIN/0812989783/braipick-20?mc_cid=3D1ffb15db80&mc_eid=3D=
[UNIQID]) with Sontag on selfies=2C selfhood=2C and how the camera helps=
 us navigate complexity (https://www.brainpickings.org/2016/03/30/susan-so=
ntag-photography-interview/?mc_cid=3D1ffb15db80&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) and th=
is animated history of photography (https://www.brainpickings.org/2016/08/=
25/animated-history-of-photography/?mc_cid=3D1ffb15db80&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]=
) =2C from the camera obscura to the camera phone=2C then revisit Israel R=
osenfield=E2=80=99s trailblazing exploration of consciousness=2C memory=2C=
 and how our sense of self arises (https://www.brainpickings.org/2016/03/1=
7/the-strange-familiar-and-forgotten-israel-rosenfield/?mc_cid=3D1ffb15db8=
0&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) .


