 30px 10px 0px;display: inline;width: 50px!important;">Photography is ines=
capably a memorial art. It selects=2C out of the flow of time=2C a moment=
 to be preserved=2C with the moments before and after falling away like sh=
eer cliffs. At a dinner party earlier this year=2C I was in conversation w=
ith someone who asked me to define photography. I suggested that it is abo=
ut retention: not only the ability to make an image directly out of the in=
teraction between light and the tangible world but also the possibility of=
 saving that image. A shadow thrown onto a wall is not photography. But if=
 the wall is photosensitive and the shadow remains after the body has move=
d on=2C that is photography. Human creativity=2C since the beginning of ar=
t=2C has found ways to double the visible world. What photography did was=
 to give the world a way to double its own appearance: the photograph resu=
